                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1830" notAfter="1866">
                        <p>Probably rebound in <placeName
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                              >London</placeName> for <persName type="standard"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580" role="fmo"
                              change="#role-assignment">Duncan Forbes</persName>. </p>
                        <p>Sewn on five recessed cords, laced into <material>pasteboards</material>.
                           Endpapers of heavy-weight British-made wove added at the beginning and
                           end. Edges trimmed and spattered russet brown. Front-bead decorative
                           endbands of peach and green silk threads sewn at <locus from="Head"
                              to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>.
                           Covered in half British tan coloured calfskin
                              <material>leather</material>, tight-backed, and faced with
                           predominantly green straight-waved "Spanish"-patterned marbled paper. </p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Spine panels paletted with triple fillet lines and
                           bear the title and volume number, all in gold. Blind triple fillet lines
                           adjacent to the marbled paper facing. Note that the same binder also
                           evidently completed <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7330"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 822</idno></ref> and others, probably for
                           Forbes.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>300</height>
                              <width>213</width>
                              <depth>59</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable condition, with
                           exterior abrasion to the board edges and torn headcaps, and opening to
                           the gutter margins restricted.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <summary>Folios <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears four black seal
                        impressions, with two obliterated but still identifiable as that of former
                        owner <persName key="person_f6463" role="ins seal ato fmo" xml:lang="en">
                           William Oliver</persName>, as well as a small black oval seal on <locus
                           from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>, and another small black rectangular
                        impression on <locus from="512a" to="560a">560a</locus>.</summary>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="relief">
                        <p><label>1:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>,
                           centre-right, bears a black relief-cut Latin script impression of the
                           initials <q xml:lang="en">W*O</q> of former owner <persName
                              key="person_f6463" role="ins seal ato fmo" xml:lang="en"> William
                              Oliver</persName>, since obliterated.<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>21.5</height>
                              <width>26</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="octagon">
                        <p><label>2:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>,
                           bottom-right, also bears an Anglo-Persian, black octagonal seal
                           impression, intaglio-carved in one nastaliq line, double-ruled, with the
                           name of former owner <persName key="person_f6463" role="ins seal ato fmo"
                              xml:lang="en"> William Oliver</persName> dated <date
                              calendar="#Gregorian" when="1804">1804</date>, since obliterated:<lb/>
                        <q xml:lang="fa"><persName type="person" role="fmo" xml:lang="fa">ولیم
                                 اولر ۱۸۰۴</persName>.</q>
                        <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>21.5</height>
                              <width>26</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                        <p><label>3:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, centre-left,
                           bears a large legible oval seal impression, intaglio-carved in three
                           nasta‘līq lines read from bottom up, with the name of former owner
                              <persName role="fmo seal ins">Mīrzā Muḥammad Fidvī</persName>, dated
                              <date cert="medium" calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1737" to="1738"
                              >1150 AH (1737–1738 CE)</date>, during the reign of the Mughal Emperor
                              <persName role="asn" key="person_45680638"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/45680638">Muḥammad Shāh (b. 1702, r.
                              1719–1748)</persName>:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa">میر تقی علی فدوی بادشاه غازی محمد فرخ سیر عالمگیر ثانی </q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>22</height>
                              <width>31</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>4:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, top edge,
                           bears a small legible rectangular seal impression, intaglio-carved in two
                           naskh lines read from bottom up, single-ruled, that invokes the
                              <persName>Prophet Muḥammad</persName>, possibly dated <date
                              cert="medium" calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1731" to="1732">1144 AH
                              (1731–1732 CE)</date>, hence probably a namesake seal for a former
                           owner by that name, adjacent to his trimmed inscription:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar">يا محمد</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>9</height>
                              <width>11</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="rectangle">
                        <p><label>5:</label> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus>, top, bears a
                           small, legible rectangular seal impression, intaglio-carved in two naskh
                           lines read from bottom up, single-ruled, that bears the name of a former
                           owner named <persName role="seal fmo"> Muḥammad Ḥusyan</persName>, dated
                              <date cert="medium" calendar="#Hijri-qamari" from="1739" to="1740"
                              >1152 AH (1739–1740 CE)</date>, adjacent to his inscription:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="fa">محمد حسين</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>10</height>
                              <width>12</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                        <p><label>6:</label> Folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>, top-right,
                           bears a small legible seal oval impression intaglio-carved in two naskh
                           script lines read from bottom, double-ruled, upward bearing an Arabic
                           quote from the <title>Qur'ān, Sūrah Muḥammad</title> verse 2 (47:2),
                           hence probably a namesake seal for a former owner by that name:<lb/>
                           <q xml:lang="ar">وَآمَنُوا بِمَا نُزِّلَ عَلَىٰ مُحَمَّدٍ</q><lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>10</height>
                              <width>13</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal type="stamp" subtype="oval">
                        <p><label>7:</label> A small rectangular black impression in two nasta‘līq
                           lines bears the <hi rend="italic">Shahadah</hi> and may represent a
                           namesake seal of someone named <persName cert="medium" role="seal"
                              >Muḥammad</persName>:<lb/>
                           <dimensions type="seal" unit="mm">
                              <height>10</height>
                              <width>13</width>
                           </dimensions></p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
